{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"72088978-1564-412f-814a-3d470fb1fe90","content":"PID 12345 isn't currently running on this machine, but here's exactly how to diagnose the runtime and configure dumps when your app is live.\n\n## 1. Determine CoreCLR vs NativeAOT\n\nRun these checks against your process:\n\n```bash\n# Method 1: Check if libcoreclr.so is loaded (CoreCLR-specific)\ncat /proc/<PID>/maps | grep -q libcoreclr && echo \"CoreCLR\" || echo \"Likely NativeAOT\"\n\n# Method 2: Check for dotnet host vs standalone binary\nls -la /proc/<PID>/exe\n# CoreCLR: usually points to /usr/share/dotnet/dotnet or a host\n# NativeAOT: points to your app binary directly\n\n# Method 3: Check loaded shared libraries\ncat /proc/<PID>/maps | grep -E 'libcoreclr|libhostfxr|libclrjit'\n# If none found → NativeAOT (single self-contained binary, no JIT)\n```\n\n## 2. Configure Crash Dumps\n\n### For CoreCLR apps:\n\n```bash\n# Set environment variables before launching your app:\nexport DOTNET_DbgEnableMiniDump=1\nexport DOTNET_DbgMiniDumpType=4          # 1=Mini, 2=Heap, 3=Triage, 4=Full\nexport DOTNET_DbgMiniDumpName=/tmp/dumps/coredump.%p.%t\n\nmkdir -p /tmp/dumps\n```\n\n### For NativeAOT apps:\n\nNativeAOT doesn't use the `DOTNET_Dbg*` variables. Use the **OS-level** core dump mechanism instead:\n\n```bash\n# Set core dump pattern\necho '/tmp/dumps/core.%p.%t' | sudo tee /proc/sys/kernel/core_pattern\n\n# Remove core file size limit\nulimit -c unlimited\n\nmkdir -p /tmp/dumps\n```\n\n### For either runtime (belt-and-suspenders):\n\nYou can safely set **both** — CoreCLR vars are ignored by NativeAOT, and `ulimit`/`core_pattern` works for everything:\n\n```bash\n# OS-level (works for both)\nulimit -c unlimited\necho '/tmp/dumps/core.%p.%t' | sudo tee /proc/sys/kernel/core_pattern\n\n# CoreCLR-specific (harmless if NativeAOT)\nexport DOTNET_DbgEnableMiniDump=1\nexport DOTNET_DbgMiniDumpType=4\nexport DOTNET_DbgMiniDumpName=/tmp/dumps/coredump.%p.%t\n\nmkdir -p /tmp/dumps\n```\n\n## 3. Analyzing Dumps\n\n```bash\n# CoreCLR dumps — use dotnet-dump:\ndotnet tool install -g dotnet-dump\ndotnet-dump analyze /tmp/dumps/coredump.<pid>.<time>\n\n# NativeAOT dumps — use lldb/gdb (no managed debugger support):\nlldb --core /tmp/dumps/core.<pid>.<time> /path/to/your/app\n```\n\n**TL;DR:** Check `/proc/<PID>/maps` for `libcoreclr.so`. If present → CoreCLR (use `DOTNET_DbgEnableMiniDump`). If absent → NativeAOT (use `kernel.core_pattern` + `ulimit -c unlimited`). Setting both is safe.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"abb786c0-fa2c-458e-9b14-91a3a599b2b0","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The process isn't running, but I can still guide the user on how to determine the runtime and configure dumps. Let me provide a comprehensive guide.","outputTokens":902,"requestId":"2C61:97105:1421BF6:16F4289:69F94E6F"},"id":"4ece7039-578e-4b65-b3ae-a458579e2186","timestamp":"2026-05-05T01:57:36.119Z","parentId":"6b0b4ba7-1a76-45d0-b589-9213287ca1b3"}
